 (see   Bert  ). See also Scottish   Beaton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Beaton","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Béthune in Pas-de-Calais, France (see   Bethune  ). The Hebridean family of   McBeth  , hereditary physicians, adopted the surname <i>Beaton</i> in the 16th century.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Beton</i>, a diminutive of <i>Bete</i>, a pet form of <i>Beatrice</i> (see   Beatrice  ). Compare   Beat  .","English: variant of   Betton  ."]},{"name":"Bert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philibert, Pierre.","German, French, and Polish: from a short form of various compound personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ (see for example   Bertram  ).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Berte</i> (Old French <i>Berte</i>, from ancient Germanic   Berta  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Bethune II, 3rd of Balfour was born about 1370, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, John de Bethune 1st of Balfour, was 31 and his mother, Catherine Stewart, was 25. He married Jean Stewart about 1395, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1421, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1370–Aft 1421":"umbes 1370–pärast 1421","1370–1421":"1370–1421","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1418–1499":"1418–1499","1340–1420":"1340–1420","1346–1386":"1346–1386","Aft 1421":"pärast 1421","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Abt 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1418":"umbes 1418","1346":"1346","1499":"1499","1421":"1421","1420":"1420","1386":"1386","1375":"1375","1418":"1418","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scot